Contents of the data

Data is from an international survey of approaches to learning, made possible by teachers. The data is used as a course material in a course called Introduction to Open Data Science and it consists of seven variables and 166 observations.

Variable contets briefly:

  • gender = gender of the respondent (categorical)
  • age = age of the respondent (integer)
  • attitude = Global attitude toward statistics/10 (numerical)
  • deep = mean of the values related to deep learning methods (numerical)
  • stra = mean of the values related to strategic learning methods (numerical)
  • surf = mean of the values related to surface learning methods (numerical)
  • points = exam points (integer)

Testing the model

The selected three explanatory variables are: stra, surf and deep. Response variable is called points.

my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf + deep, data = student2014)

Only attitude seems to correlate with the exam points (p = 1.34e-08, p<0.001). To make a model that fits better, I will remove the non-significant variables from the model.

Removing the excess variables from the model

## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

Now the model should fit the data better. Intercept is 11.6372 and slope is 3.5255. The p value tests whether the estimates for the intercept and slope are equal to zero eg. the variable has no effect in the model. In this case, p value is even smaller than in the first model (p = 4.12e-09 p<0.001) indicating that the studentâs attitude has an effect to exam points. Multiple R-squared indicates that 19 percent of the variation in exam points is explained by the studentâs attitude.

Assumptions of the model based on diagnostic plots

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(my_model2, which = c(1, 2, 5))

Residuals vs.Â leverage provides information on whether there are influential data points that might disturb the model by being for example mistakes in the data. Residuals might be skewed since there is a change in the spread of the values with smaller leverage having higher spread than the ones with higher leverage. When looking at all of the plots, it seems like entries 145, 56 and 35 might be outliers, that should be checked in case of a mistake in the data. Otherwise qq-plot distribution is relatively close to the line. Also the residuals vs.Â fitted plot looks otherwise good.

Data consists of questionnaires about alcohol consumption of secondary school students in Portugal. Data has variables concerning grades, demography, social features and school features. Dataset is a combination of two datasets addressing the effect of these variables on mathematics and Portuguese. There are 370 observations and 35 variables,

Relationship between high and low alcohol consumption on a selection of variables

I am investigating whether age, absence, sex or higher have an effect on whether the student consumes high or low amounts of alcohol.

  • Age - studentâs age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
  • Absence = number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)
  • Sex = studentâs sex (binary: âFâ - female or âMâ - male)
  • Higher = wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)

Hypotheses

  • age is not expected to have an effect on the alcohol consumption
  • number of school absences is higher when the level of alcohol consumption increases
  • males are predicted to have higher alcohol consumption than females.
  • students that want to take higher education use less alcohol than students that do not want to do so.

Logistic regression

Relationship between the chosen variables and the high/low alcohol consumption. The chosen variables are age, absence, sex, higher

m1 <- glm(high_use ~ age + absences + sex + higher, data = studentalc, family = "binomial")
# summary of the model

Number of absences and male gender had significant effects on the probability of using high amounts of alcohol just as was hypothesized. Age did not have a significant effect on alcohol use, which was also expected. Plans on getting a higher education did not have an effect on the probability of a student to use high amounts of alcohol. However, there were only 15 students that did not plan on getting a higher education. Males were almost three times more likely using high amounts of alcohol than females. Also the as number of absences increased by one, increased the odds that the student uses high amounts of alcohol by 1.09.

Predictive power of my model

# variables wit a statistical relationship with alcohol consumption
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ absences + sex, data = studentalc, family = "binomial")

# probability of high use (prediction)
probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")

# predicted probabilities to the original data
studentalc <- mutate(studentalc, probability = probabilities)

# prediction of high use
studentalc <- mutate(studentalc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# how it looks like? 
select(studentalc, absences, sex, high_use, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

Divide the dataset into train and test sets (80% to the train set)

# number of rows
nrow(boston_scaled)
## [1] 506
n <- 506

# randomly select 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# create the train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# and the test set
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

# correct classes from the test data 
correct_classes <- test$crime

# remove the crime variable from test data
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

# biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# LDA plot
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)
